 We know that it will take Tom 4 hours to catch up with Bob. We can use this time to calculate the distance between them. 

First, we find the time it takes for Tom to catch up by subtracting the distance from the initial lead, then multiply by the speed of Tom's car. 

 \text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}} 
 \text{Time} = \frac{75 \text{ miles}}{70 \text{ mph}} 
 \text{Time} = 1.14 \text{ hours} 

Since we're calculating the time in hours, we'll convert the time to hours and then multiply it by 3600 (since 1 hour = 3600 seconds).

 \text{Time in hours} = 1.14 \text{ hours} \times 3600 \text{ seconds/hour} 
 \text{Time in hours} = 4140 \text{ seconds} 

Now, we can find the distance covered by Tom in the same time frame. 

 \text{Distance} = \text{Speed} \times \text{Time} 
 \text{Distance} = 70 \text{ mph} \times 4140 \text{ seconds} 
 \text{Distance} = 287,200 \text{ miles} 

Now, we can find the distance between Tom and Bob. 

 \text{Distance between Bob and Tom} = \text{Distance of Tom} - \text{Distance of Bob} 
 \text{Distance between Bob and Tom} = 287,200 \text{ miles} - 75 \text{ miles} 
 \text{Distance between Bob and Tom} = 286,225 \text{ miles} 

Now, we can find the distance between Tom and Bob. 

 \text{Distance between Tom and Bob} = \text{Distance of Tom} - \text{Distance of Bob} 
 \text{Distance between Tom and Bob} = 287,200 \text{ miles} - 75 \text{ miles} 
 \text{Distance between Tom and Bob} = 286,225 \text{ miles} 

Now, we can find the time it will take Tom to catch up with Bob. 

 \text{Time to catch up} = \frac{\text{Distance between Tom and Bob}}{\text{Speed of Tom's car}} 
 \text{Time to catch up} = \frac{286,225 \text{ miles}}{70 \text{ mph}} 
 \text{Time to catch up} = 4.14 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, it will take Tom 4.14 hours to catch up with Bob.
The answer is: 4.14 hours

