  First, we need to find out how far James walked from his home to the store.  Since he walked 4 miles per hour and he was halfway there, he has already covered half of the distance to the store.  This means he needs to cover the remaining distance, which is the other half of the journey.  The distance he needs to cover is 
 \frac{1}{2} \times 4 \text{ miles} = 2 \text{ miles} 
Since he walks 4 miles per hour, he will take 
 \frac{2 \text{ miles}}{4 \text{ mph}} = \frac{1}{2} \text{ hours} = 30 \text{ minutes} 
To convert minutes to hours, we multiply by 60 since there are 60 minutes in an hour 30 \text{ minutes} \times 60 = 2 \text{ hours} 
Therefore, it took James 2 hours to walk from his home to the store.
The answer is: 2 hours

 First, we need to calculate the total number of minutes in a week for John to attend classes and then calculate the extra time spent on Saturday and Sunday. There are 168 hours in a week, so
 \text{Total minutes per week} = 6 \text{ periods} \times 60 \text{ minutes/period} + 5 \text{ days} \times 24 \text{ minutes/day} + 1 \text{ hour} 
 \text{Total minutes per week} = 6 \times 60 + 120 + 60 = 216 \text{ minutes} 
Since John attends classes for 5 days a week, he spends \frac{1}{16} of his weekly minutes on Saturday and Sunday. This means he spends \frac{5}{16} of his weekly minutes on Saturday and Sunday. We can calculate the total time spent on Saturday and Sunday as follows
 \text{Time spent on Saturday and Sunday} = \frac{5}{16} \times 24 \text{ minutes/day} 
 \text{Time spent on Saturday and Sunday} = \frac{120}{16} \text{ minutes} 
 \text{Time spent on Saturday and Sunday} = 7.5 \text{ minutes} 
However, since we're asked for hours, we convert minutes to hours by multiplying by 60
 \text{Total hours per week} = 216 \text{ minutes} \times 60 \text{ minutes/hour} 
 \text{Total hours per week} = 12960 \text{ minutes} 
 \text{Total hours per week} = 12960 \text{ minutes} \times 60 \text{ minutes/hour} 
 \text{Total hours per week} = 77760 \text{ minutes} 
Therefore, John spends 77760 minutes learning each week.
The answer is: 77760 minutes

