 First, we need to find the circumference of the earth, which is given as 40,000 kilometers. Since Alfie flies 400 kilometers per day, we can calculate the total distance he covers in a day as follows
 \text{Distance covered in a day} = 400 \text{ km/day} \times 24 \text{ hours/day} 
 \text{Distance covered in a day} = 9,600 \text{ km} 

Now, we can use the formula for the circumference of a circle, C = d, where d is the distance covered in a day, to find the time it takes for Alfie to fly half of the way around the earth
 C = \pi \times 40,000 \text{ km} 
 t = \frac{C}{d} 
 t = \frac{\pi \times 40,000 \text{ km}}{40,000 \text{ km}} 
 t = 1 \text{ day} 

Since Alfie flies 400 kilometers per day, we can calculate the total distance he covers in a day as follows
 \text{Distance covered in a day} = 400 \text{ km/day} \times 24 \text{ hours/day} 
 \text{Distance covered in a day} = 9,600 \text{ km} 

Now, we can use the formula for the time it takes for Alfie to fly half of the way around the earth, t, to find the number of days
 t = \frac{C}{d} 
 t = \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{C}{d} 
 t = \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{\pi \times 40,000 \text{ km}}{40,000 \text{ km}} 
 t = 1 \text{ day} 

However, since we are looking for the number of days it takes for Alfie to fly half of the way around the earth, we need to consider the full period of time, which is 24 hours. Therefore, the correct calculation for the number of days is
 \text{Number of days} = \frac{1}{24} \times \frac{C}{d} 
 \text{Number of days} = \frac{1}{24} \times \frac{\pi \times 40,000 \text{ km}}{40,000 \text{ km}} 
 \text{Number of days} = \frac{1}{24} \times 1 \text{ day} 
 \text{Number of days} = 0.0417 \text{ days} 

Since we cannot have a fraction of a day in this context, we round up to the nearest whole number. Therefore, it will take Alfie approximately 1 day to fly half of the way around the earth.

The answer is: 1 day

