 First, we need to calculate the total volume of the jar in cubic inches. The volume of the jar is given by V = s^2h, where s is the side length of the square (6 inches) and h is the height (15 inches). We can rearrange this to solve for s V = \frac{s^2}{6^2} \times 15 \text{ inches} 
 V = \frac{36}{36} \times 15 \text{ inches} 
 V = 1 \text{ inch}^3 
Now, we know that a jelly bean is 0.15 cubic inches. Since the jar is filled with jelly beans, we can calculate the total number of jelly beans by N = V \times \text{density} 
 N = 1 \text{ inch}^3 \times 0.15 \text{ in}^3/\text{bean} 
 N = 0.15 \text{ beans} 
Given that there are 900 jelly beans in the jar, we can find the number of red jelly beans by R = 0.3 \times 0.15 \text{ in}^3/\text{bean} 
 R = 0.45 \text{ beans} 
Now, we can find the percentage of red jelly beans by P = \frac{R}{N} \times 100\% 
 P = \frac{0.45}{0.15} \times 100\% 
 P = 3\% 
Since Tim guessed 30% of the jelly beans were red, his guess was 3% off. Therefore, the correct number of red jelly beans in the jar is 900 - 270 = 630.
The answer is: 630

